<tt>Fri Jan  2 20:10:28 US/Eastern 1998
</tt><p>
Charles,<br><br>
You said:<br><br>
&quot;Paradox: a movement that works take the freedom away that<br>
permits the movement itself to exist.&quot;<br><br>
I follow your logic to your conclusion. In fact, had the US been a totalitarian state, I would have been hailed as a &quot;Hero of the State&quot;, decorated like a baroque statue, and treated whith respect and deference, instead of being spat upon, sworn at, and degraded, discriminated against, called a &quot;baby killer&quot; and all those undesireable things that continue to befall Vietnam Veterans to this day. <br><br>
The present regime in Vietnam pulls out fingernails in the backroom with pliers while smiling like cheshire cats at the world. The Bhuddists are again being persecuted! Personally, I see nothing for which the &quot;protestors&quot; who did not pull their weight can be proud. Their ideology falls flat on its face.<br><br>
I respect protestors whose sincere religous convictions placed them into alternative roles. I respect protestors who respect the choices I made in dealing with the situation. The anarchists are another matter, for that is what they were. Their self serving narrow perspectives forced a miniature &quot;war of civil disobedience&quot; for which there were no winners. Both the US and its people lost, as did the people of Vietnam. I have absolutely no use for such individuals.<br><br>
There are many paradoxes in the conflict, as well as the &quot;protest&quot; movement. It can be argued that fortunes were made by civilian contractors whose wealth increased as the death toll rose, on purpose. It can be argued that the political leaders and the military brass were corrupt and fought the war in a way that could not be won. These paradoxes, and many others, will be the subject of debate for years to come. <br><br>
Suggested reading: &quot;Nam, the Vietnam Experience, 1965-1975&quot;,<br>
Barnes and Noble, 1994, ISBN 1-56619-949-2
